
= Why is Luwrain different than other accessible solutions? =

Current popular solutions offer Graphical User Interface (GUI) environment 
in~conjunction with additional screen reading software.
Screen readers  speak every action user does through some Text-To-Speech (TTS) engine. 
This type of~interaction with~GUI can be done only by~keyboard navigation 
and that makes impossible the~same speed of~work as~sighted users have.
There is~no way to~overcome this restriction because 
GUI is~designed to~be~comfort with~a~mouse only
and there are no ideas how to~change that.

Roughly speaking, blind people have~to struggle with the~environment the~least suitable for~them,
but the~truth is~that this~problem is~totally artificial.
GUI has been created by~the~hands of~other people, it is popular but not the single form of~using  PCs.
There can be~other conceptions, likely, more fortunate 
for~accessible solutions.

Luwrain offers hybrid approach that uses GUI only for~very specific tasks, like web-browsing.
Surfing over the~web is~possible with traditional browsing software only,
but other tasks, hopefully,  could be reconsidered in~some other way.
The~idea Luwrain follows is a~text-based interface  
that invites user into the~friendly working area with no~items potentially inaccessible within it.
Inside of~the~new environment the~applications  decide by~themselves what information 
provide in~speech form and what information print on~the~monitor. 
The~screen is~filled only with well-readable content relevant to~user active data.
Special algorithm decides what part of data should be~printed and how it~should be placed.
For~visually impaired persons Luwrain offers set of~system-wide settings 
to~get comfortable  font size, comfortable colors etc.

Any text-based systems are not a~revelation in~area of~accessibility research, 
but Luwrain looks for~text-based design 
that could be~functionally equal to~GUI and could save common integrity,
which is~needed for~easy understanding by~application developers.
It's rather difficult task, but we sure it~is~possible.

